e medial consonant. Alternatively, the name may also be from a Middle English rhyming pet form of <i>Roger</i> (see   Dodge  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-et</i>. But whether the medial <i>-g-</i> was pronounced as a stop /g/ (as in <i>dog</i>) or an affricate /dʒ/ (as in <i>Roger</i>) is impossible to tell."],"variants":[{"name":"Duckett","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Duket</i>. This may sometimes have been an early Middle English pet form of an Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i>, but was more often a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorkshire (see   Duke  ). <i>Marmaduke</i> itself is from Irish <i>Maol Maedóc</i> ‘servant of Maedóc’, <i>Maedóc</i> being the name of prominent Irish saints of the 6th and 7th centuries."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lan